            <!-- Explanation -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this molarity calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Molarity (symbol <strong>M</strong>) is defined as the number of
                moles of solute per liter of solution:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1 text-center font-medium">Molarity definition</p>
                <p class="text-center">\( M = \dfrac{n}{V} \)</p>
                <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-600 mt-1">
                  where \( n \) is moles of solute (mol) and \( V \) is solution
                  volume (L).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>From mass and molar mass to molarity</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the solute mass and its molar mass, the calculator
                first converts mass to moles:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( n = \dfrac{m}{M_r} \)</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-1">
                  where \( m \) is mass (g) and \( M_r \) is molar mass
                  (g·mol\(^{-1}\)).
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                It then divides by the solution volume in liters to obtain
                molarity:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( M = \dfrac{m / M_r}{V_{\text{(L)}}} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Unit handling</h3>
              <p>The tool automatically converts between:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Mass units: g, mg, µg</li>
                <li>Volume units: L, mL, µL</li>
                <li>Concentration units: M, mM, µM</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Internally, all calculations are done in moles and liters, then
                converted back to the unit you selected for display.
              </p>

              <h3>Dilution calculator (C₁V₁ = C₂V₂)</h3>
              <p>For dilutions, the calculator uses the standard equation:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( C_1 V_1 = C_2 V_2 \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                You can leave exactly one of C₁, V₁, C₂, or V₂ blank; the
                calculator rearranges the equation to solve for the missing
                variable, for example:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>\( V_1 = \dfrac{C_2 V_2}{C_1} \)</li>
                <li>\( C_2 = \dfrac{C_1 V_1}{V_2} \)</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                <strong>Example:</strong> What mass of NaCl (M<sub>r</sub> =
                58.44 g/mol) is needed to prepare 250 mL of 0.20 M solution?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert volume to liters: 250 mL = 0.250 L.</li>
                <li>
                  Find moles: \( n = M \times V = 0.20 \times 0.250 = 0.050
                  \,\text{mol} \).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Convert moles to mass: \( m = n \times M_r = 0.050 \times
                  58.44 \approx 2.92 \,\text{g} \).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                In the calculator, choose <em>Mass from molarity</em>, enter
                0.20 M, 250 mL, and 58.44 g/mol. It will return approximately
                2.92 g NaCl.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What is molarity?</h3>
              <p>
                Molarity is the concentration of a solution expressed as moles
                of solute per liter of solution. A 1.0 M solution contains 1.0
                mole of solute in every liter of total solution volume.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I calculate molarity from mass and volume?</h3>
              <p>Use these steps:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert the solute mass to moles: \( n = m / M_r \).</li>
                <li>Convert the solution volume to liters.</li>
                <li>Compute \( M = n / V \).</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator performs all conversions automatically when you
                enter mass, molar mass, and volume.
              </p>

              <h3>How accurate is this molarity calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator uses double‑precision floating‑point arithmetic
                and keeps several significant figures internally. Rounding in
                the displayed result is for readability; you can always adjust
                the number of decimals by interpreting the raw values.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this for very dilute or very concentrated solutions?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The unit selectors (M, mM, µM; L, mL, µL) make it
                convenient to work with both very dilute and relatively
                concentrated solutions. For extremely concentrated or non‑ideal
                solutions, activity coefficients may become important, but those
                are beyond simple molarity.
              </p>

              <h3>Is molarity temperature‑dependent?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Because molarity is based on volume, and volume changes
                slightly with temperature, molarity also changes with
                temperature. For most routine lab work at room temperature, this
                effect is small. If you need temperature‑independent
                concentration, consider molality (mol/kg solvent) instead.
              </p>
